  "prompt": "Is it normal to have a dark ring around the iris of my eye?",
  "response": "A dark ring around the iris, known as a limbal ring, is actually quite common and normal. Here are some details:\n\n1. Natural occurrence\n- Many people have limbal rings\n- They are typically more prominent in younger people\n- The ring is caused by a high contrast between the iris and the sclera (white part of the eye)\n\n2. Age-related changes\n- Limbal rings tend to become less pronounced as people age\n- They can fade or become less defined over time\n\n3. Potential variations\n- The ring's darkness and prominence can differ between individuals\n- Some people have more visible rings than others\n\n4. When to be concerned\n- If the ring is new, suddenly appears, or is accompanied by other symptoms\n- If you experience pain, vision changes, or discoloration\n- In rare cases, it could indicate a medical condition\n\nIf you're worried about the appearance of the ring or experience any unusual symptoms, it's best to consult an eye care professional who can provide a personalized assessment.",
